reasoning: Etruscan civilization and Greek civilization are distinct cultural entities with different origins, histories, and identities. They are related historically (interaction with Rome and each other) but are not the same entity and should not be merged.

Both entries clearly refer to the same collective people: the Etruscan(s) who inhabited and influenced early Rome. The names differ only in singular vs. plural and the descriptions and attributes (literacy from a Greek-derived alphabet, loose league of city-kings, dominance in early Rome, archaeological record) all describe the same historical group.

One entity is a people (Etruscans) and the other is a region (Etruria). They are closely related (the Etruscans inhabited Etruria), but they are different types (collective people vs place/region). Therefore they should not be merged.

The first entity is a geographic region (Greece). The second is a cultural label (Greek) referring to the culture/language of the Greeks; it is related to but not identical with the place. They are distinct entity types (place vs culture) and represent related but different concepts, so they should not be merged.

The two entities refer to different concepts: one denotes the Roman people (the citizen body/people of Rome), a social/political collective; the other denotes the Roman Empire, a territorial/political state. They are related but not identical and should not be merged.

'Roman people' (the people/citizen assemblies of Rome) refers specifically to the citizen body of Rome. 'Latin peoples' are the various Latin-speaking communities (Latins) who challenged Etruscan power and then went their own ways; they are a distinct set of peoples and an ethnolinguistic group that predate and are related to early Romans but are not identical to the Roman people. These are related but not the same entity.

Both mentions refer to the Roman consul/magistracy. Entity 1 describes the pair of consuls (collective office-holders) instituted at the end of the sixth century BC with one-year terms and rule through the Senate; Entity 2 describes the consul as the highest magistracy held by nobles. They are the same historical institution (the consulship), with one phrasing emphasizing the office as held by two people and the other emphasizing the office as the highest magistracy. Differences are a matter of framing, not distinct entities.

The two entities refer to different concepts: 'Roman society' denotes the broader social body and way of life in Rome (a population/collective of people and their social structure), whereas the 'Roman Senate' is a specific political institution/organization within Roman society. They are related (the Senate is part of Roman society) but not identical.

The two entities refer to different things: one is an event/procedure (the Roman census), the other is an institutional body (the Roman Senate). They are related (the Senate was involved in governance that used census data) but not identical.

Both names refer to the same political entity — the Roman Republic. "Early republic" is a temporal subset of the Roman Republic, but in extraction context both are labeled as the same collective_entity/state and the descriptions point to the Roman Republic. They are not distinct entities like 'early period' vs 'the whole republic' for KG unique-ness; they should be merged as the canonical political entity 'Roman Republic'.
The two entities are different centuries (fifth century BC vs tenth century BC), representing distinct time periods. They are not the same historical entity and should not be merged.

These are two distinct centuries (fifth century BC vs seventh century BC). They are different time intervals and not the same historical entity. They are related as temporal periods but not identical.

The Athenian empire (the empire of Athens) and the Roman Empire are distinct historical states: different polities, time periods, geography, and institutions. They are related as empires and used comparatively in the text, but they are not the same entity and should not be merged.

Both entries clearly refer to the people of Rome (singular vs plural naming and slightly different descriptions). They describe the same collective group: Romans who supplanted Etruscan power and valued continuity of republican traditions. Therefore they should be merged.

Entity 1 refers to the people/citizen body of Rome (the Romans), a collective social/political group. Entity 2 refers to the city/place of Rome. These are related but distinct: one is a population/people/civic community, the other is a geographic/political city. They are not strictly the same entity and should not be merged.

The Samnite peoples and the Latin peoples are distinct historical ethnic/tribal groups in ancient Italy. The Samnites were tribes from the Abruzzi/central-southern Apennines; the Latins were the peoples of Latium who interacted with and later dominated or allied with Rome. They are related as contemporaneous Italic groups but are not the same entity.

The two names refer to different regional concepts: 'western Mediterranean' denotes the western part of the Mediterranean basin (a geographic/political theater contested between Rome and Carthage), while 'Roman Mediterranean' describes the Mediterranean as reorganized and dominated by Rome (an imperial/administrative region made possible by Roman institutions). They are related (overlap geographically and historically) but are not strictly identical—the first is a geographic subregion, the second is a Roman-created imperial sphere.

The two entities refer to different concepts: one is the territorial/administrative divisions of Roman territory ('Roman provinces'), while the other refers to the body of Roman citizens or populace ('Roman people' / 'the people'). They are related (provinces were governed on behalf of Rome and its people), but they are not the same historical entity and should not be merged.

One refers to 'Greek cities' (cities in Spain promised Roman protection) — a group of individual Greek city communities in a geographic/temporal context. The other refers to 'Greek city-states' as a political form (city-state/polis) similar to Rome's assemblies. These are related concepts (both about Greek poleis) but not strictly the same extracted entity: one is a specific set of Greek cities in Spain (a particular group/location/context), the other is the general political form (Greek city-states/poleis). They are not identical and should not be merged.

Both names refer to Greek cities as a collective group; one phrase is simply more specific ('western Greek cities') but does not indicate a different entity type. The two mentions appear to denote the same category of entities (Greek cities), with the second merely specifying a geographic subset. Without evidence that 'western Greek cities' refers to a distinct, separate organized entity, they should be treated as the same collective entity for normalization, while the geographic qualifier can be recorded in descriptions or attributes if needed.

New Carthage (Cartagena) is a different city founded as a Phoenician/Carthaginian colony on the Iberian coast and captured by the Romans in 209 BC. Carthage refers to the ancient city-state in North Africa (and the Carthaginian state) that was Rome's rival. They are distinct places and political entities, not the same entity.

New Carthage (a city, also called Cartagena) is a place. Carthaginians (the people/collective, Carthaginian power) are the people/state associated with Carthage and its colonies in Spain. They are related (the city was established/held by Carthaginians and involved in the Second Punic War) but are different entity types (place vs people/collective), so they should not be merged.

The two names refer to different wars in the Punic Wars series: the Second Punic War (famous conflict with Hannibal, 218–201 BC) and the Third Punic War (the final war beginning in 149 BC). They are related but distinct events, so they should not be merged.

Both mentions refer to the same collective group: the people of Carthage (Carthaginians). The descriptions overlap (people of Carthage, involved in the Second Punic War, overcome by Rome). Variants differ only in pluralization and an alias phrase. No evidence they refer to different subsets or time periods.

One entity is a people/collective (the Carthaginians); the other is a specific city/place (New Carthage / Cartagena). They are related (city founded/held by Carthaginians and captured by Rome in 209 BC) but are different types and not the same single historical entity, so they should not be merged.

The term 'satellites' as described (“Groups subordinate to the Roman empire providing manpower”) is a generic category of subordinate peoples or states, not a specific ethnic group. 'Samnite peoples' (Samnites) are a specific ethnic group from the Abruzzi conquered by Rome and could be examples of such subordinate peoples, but they are not identical to the general category 'satellites'. Therefore they should not be merged.

Both entries refer to the same concept: the administrative divisions of the Roman state commonly called Roman provinces. The first is a generic label 'provinces' described as the basic units of the Roman Empire ruled by governors; the second explicitly names 'Roman provinces' with the same meaning. There is no indication they denote different sets, time periods, or senses, so they should be merged.

Entity 1 is a plural collective label for officials chosen by the Senate to govern new provinces; Entity 2 describes a single official (a governor) with proconsular powers serving one-year terms. These refer to the same role/type of historical office (governor) but one is a collective noun and the other is an individual instance. They are not distinct historical entities; they describe the same office. Therefore they should be merged into a single canonical entity describing the governor role.

Both descriptions refer to the same concept: territorial units governed by governors appointed by Rome/Senate, i.e., Roman provinces. "new provinces" is a vague mention but matches the definition and function of Roman provinces described in Entity 2. They are not distinct entities but the same category of administrative territorial units.

Entity 1 is a judicial body (a special court established in 149 BC to try extortion by officials). Entity 2 is a geographical/place reference (the Seleucid court/place where Hannibal was exiled). They are different in type (organization vs place) and refer to distinct concepts: a Roman special tribunal vs the Seleucid royal court/seat in the Seleucid realm. Not the same entity.

The two entities are different centuries (first century BC vs fifth century BC), distinct time periods separated by several centuries and described with different historical events. They are not the same entity and should not be merged.
These are two distinct centuries in different millennia (1st century BC vs 10th century BC). They are different time periods and not the same historical entity.

The two entities are different centuries (1st century BC vs 7th century BC). They are distinct temporal intervals and refer to different time periods and contexts (moralizing decline vs emergence of Etruscan civilization). Not the same entity.

The two entities refer to different concepts: one is the culture (a cultural phenomenon/practices/influence) of Rome, the other is the political/state entity (the Roman Empire). The two entities refer to different concepts: one is the broad cultural sphere/practices of Rome, the other is a specific administrative event/procedure (the Roman census). They are related (the census is part of Roman society) but not identical.

Transalpine Gaul (southern France, Roman province established 121 BC) and 'southern Spain' are distinct geographic regions. They refer to different parts of the Iberian Peninsula vs. Gaul/Gaulish region in what is now southern France, so they are not the same entity.

The two mentions refer to different senses: one is the Mediterranean Sea (a physical body of water where Pompey fought piracy) and the other is the Roman Mediterranean as a political/administrative region shaped by Rome's institutions. These refer to related but distinct entities: one is the Mediterranean Sea as a body of water, the other is the western Mediterranean as a subregion of that sea/region. The Julian calendar is a calendar reform introduced by Julius Caesar; it is an object/concept (cultural) distinct from the person Julius Caesar. They are related but not the same entity.

Entity 1 ('frontier provinces') refers to a subset/description of provinces at Rome's frontiers where legions were stationed; Entity 2 ('Roman provinces') denotes the general administrative territorial units of Roman rule.
